17. Hic currus fuit. This idea is taken from the custom of warrior-s, who, on their return from battle, put aside their chariots in sheds. The gods are represented as doing so likewise: see Hom. 11. viii. 441, and v. 720. In assigning a ehariot to Juno at Carthage, Virgil is more poetic than cor- rect, for there she was represented as sit- ting on a lion.
